<HL>
   Moody's Mulls
   Downgrading
   Chrysler Debt
   ---
   Review Follows Defections
   Of Four Senior Officials
   At the No. 3 Auto Maker
   ----
   By Jacqueline Mitchell and Melinda Grenier Guiles
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   C
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Moody's Investors Service Inc. said it is reviewing $22.28
billion of Chrysler Corp. debt for possible downgrade.
   The review comes in the wake of "recent management
defections" and reflects Moody's concerns about the auto
maker's "financial flexibility" to compete in an increasingly
competitive market, the credit rating service said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a statement, Moody's said its analysis will focus
primarily on the "prospects for improvement in the trend of
Chrysler's operating performance and market share in the next
several years."
   Moody's announcement came after the market closed
yesterday. In composite New York Stock Exchange trading,
Chrysler stock closed at $15.875 a share, down 37.5 cents.
   Harold H. Goldberg, chairman of Moody's corporate rating
committee, said the rating on most Chrysler debt is now "two
refined notches away from the speculative rating category."
He said Moody's hopes to decide within two weeks if ratings
will be lowered.
   Any downward move will hurt Chrysler in several ways,
including making it more expensive for the auto maker to
raise money in the credit markets and generally hurting its
financial image at a time when it doesn't need any more bad
news.
   Last month, the auto maker said it was abandoning efforts
to sell its defense-related operations because it didn't get
any satisfactory offers. But the company did sell Gulfstream
Aerospace for $825 million in March.
   Within the past five weeks, four top executives have
announced departures. Gerald Greenwald, the former vice
chairman and heir apparent to Chairman Lee A. Iacocca,
resigned late last month to head a proposed employee buy-out
at United Airlines. Bennett E. Bidwell, chairman of
Chrysler's Chrysler Motors unit, said he wants to retire on
Jan. 1, 1991 but is willing to change his plans if he is
"really needed."
   Chrysler's treasurer plans to leave this summer and the
vice president of international operations resigned to take a
top job at Black &amp; Decker Corp.
   The auto maker insists the departures are purely
coincidental, but Mr. Iacocca last week said he now will stay
at Chrysler beyond the 1991 expiration of his contract; he
didn't say how long he will remain.
   Moody's said it will examine the impact of these moves on
"the success of Chrysler's strategy to improve its
competitive position." Chrysler must sell more cars in the
future and that challenge "requires the strongest possible
management," said Moody's Mr. Goldberg.
   Moody's also will analyze Chrysler's ability to "reverse
its declining automotive market share" before new vehicles
come out in 1991 and 1992. Chrysler's share of the U.S. car
market declined sharply from February through April, with
Japanese auto makers Honda Motor Co. and Toyota Motor Corp.
besting it several times. In May, however, Chrysler's share
began to improve, even though its 9.7% slice of all cars sold
in the U.S. was still below last year's 10.9% level.
   Over the past two years, Chrysler has killed off some 20
nameplates but has been slow to bring any replacement
products to market. The company won't have a new, high-volume
car line until at least 1992; it will introduce new minivans
this fall, but updated Jeep models are still many months
away.
   Moody's noted that the "increasingly intense competitive
environment," particularly for the profitable Jeeps and
minivans, raises questions about Chrysler's ability to
generate the "substantial capital" needed to expand its
product line.
   The Highland Park, Mich., company called Moody's action
"inappropriate and unwarranted." The No. 3 U.S. auto maker
pointed to the unanticipated $5 million profit it earned in
the first quarter of 1990 on its automotive operations as
evidence that a $1.5 billion cost-cutting program it adopted
last year is working. Chrysler officials also recently noted
that the company has some $4 billion in cash and marketable
securities.
   The auto maker said it "plans to continue without
interruption its $15 billion product spending program and
believes that its business in 1990 will continue to improve."
   Among the ratings under review are the Baa-2 rating for
Chrysler Corp. senior debt and the (P)Baa-2 rating on the
company's shelf registration.
   Moody's also is reviewing ratings for Chrysler Financial
Corp., including the Baa-2 rating on its senior debt and the
Baa-3 rating on its senior subordinated debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900614-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900614-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Top Bush Aides Say Japan Is Stalling
   In Trade Talks, Press for Quick Action
   ----
   By Peter Truell and Jacob M. Schlesinger
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   Senior Bush administration officials, accusing Japan of
foot-dragging, say talks aimed at improving trade and
economic relations are stalled and that President Bush and
Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu may have to meet again soon to
defuse tensions.
   The White House is sensitive about the recent erosion in
the bilateral economic relationship because President Bush
earlier this year decided against naming Japan for unfair
trade practices under the tough Super 301 provision of the
1988 Trade Act, which carries the threat of trade
retaliation.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   U.S. critics charge that ever since that decision Japan
has stonewalled U.S. attempts to gain better access to its
markets. For example, a recent high-level U.S.-Japan meeting
in Hawaii resulted in little or no progress in resolving
issues that threaten to delay a final report -- due at the
end of the month -- on ways to resolve problems.
   The two countries began this process, called the
Structural Impediments Initiative (SII), last summer in an
attempt to reduce bilateral friction and address the U.S.'s
stubbornly high bilateral deficit with Japan. "We were
shocked at the stonewalling in Hawaii," said one senior
administration official who asked not to be named.
   Japanese officials, in return, argue that the U.S. is
pushing commitments that weren't required by the interim
report. "The main architecture is already on the table," a
foreign ministry official said. "Neither side is supposed to
add new buildings to the blueprint."
   The Japanese seem to sense that fast repair work is
needed. Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama and Vice Minister for
International Finance Makoto Utsumi are in the U.S. this week
to meet with their U.S. counterparts to discuss the SII and
other bilateral issues. Shintaro Abe, a powerful,
high-ranking leader of the Liberal Democratic Party, will
soon visit the U.S. for meetings on the 30th anniversary of
the U.S.-Japan security treaty, but will also likely hold
talks on the SII.
   Both sides agree that the most contentious issues
preventing the SII from succeeding are Japan's future level
of public spending; procedures for following up and ensuring
progress in implementing the SII report's recommendations,
and how Japan will toughen its antitrust procedures.
   Recent statements from the Japanese government saying that
the country intends to continue running a surplus equivalent
to 2% of national output have angered the Bush
administration, particularly when the U.S. is trying to
address a $49 billion deficit with Japan. A continued
Japanese surplus of that magnitude "creates a dislocation in
the trading system," U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills
said in a meeting with reporters yesterday, adding that it's
"a statement from the {Japanese} ministry of finance that
needs to be corrected."
   Others are more direct. "We're damned if we're going to
let {Japan} accumulate another half trillion dollars in trade
surpluses at our expense over the course of the next decade,"
said the senior administration official. That, he continued,
will happen if the Japanese don't open up their markets
further and increase public investment.
   Japan's recent insistence on retaining its surplus "is
purely a negotiating ploy on the part of the Ministry of
Finance of Japan," David Mulford, Treasury undersecretary for
international affairs, told reporters this week. He said it
was an attempt "to take pressure off itself to comply with
understandings it reached with the U.S. earlier this year to
increase public expenditure."
   Congress also is growing impatient. "The government of
Japan must understand that if SII doesn't meaningfully
address bilateral trade concerns, the Congress may have no
choice but to explore additional measures to address these
concerns," Sens. Robert Packwood (R., Ore.), Max Baucus (D.,
Mont.) and Jack Danforth (R., Mo.), said in a joint letter
sent to Mrs. Hills this week.
   The Japanese insist they have made progress since a
lengthy interim SII report was published in April. On May 30,
Japan revised its large retail store regulations, saying
stores must receive a permit to open within 18 months of
application. Previously, that process often dragged on for 10
years, effectively excluding many foreign stores. Also,
Japan's Fair Trade Commission has increased its staff and is
drafting antitrust changes that, the Japanese say, answer
many U.S. requests. Japan's major ministries also are mulling
further proposals for meeting U.S. concerns about the SII,
officials in Tokyo say.
   And foreign ministry officials say that the notion Japan
should preserve its surplus is a minority position advocated
by the ministry of finance. "We are aware of that view, but
the government as a whole doesn't have that as a policy," one
Japanese official said.
   But difficult problems remain. In particular, the U.S.
wants Japan to increase public spending to 10% of the gross
national product over the next 10 years. But the Japanese say
they want to use a yen total rather than a percentage of
national output. "They raised the 400 trillion yen figure,"
another senior U.S. administration official said, but he said
that "just continues the {Japanese} surplus at its current
level." Mr. Kaifu himself, in remarks to reporters over the
weekend, also said Japan was opposed to specifying
percentages of GNP, indicating strong resistance to the U.S.
approach.
   There also are disagreements over what the penalties
should be for punishing those who violate antitrust
regulations; the U.S. maintains that Japan merely imposes
small fines that amount to little more than wrist-slapping.
   The U.S. and Japan plan to exchange proposals June 20 and
then meet June 25 to finalize the SII report. But U.S.
officials question whether that will be possible. "If there's
to be a final report by the time of the Houston summit on
July 9, then we'll probably have to meet again {after the end
of June}," this official said.
   If those SII meetings do falter, President Bush and Prime
Minister Kaifu will at least get a chance to address these
issues soon. They are scheduled to hold a private bilateral
summit before the main gathering in Houston of the heads of
state of the U.S., Japan, West Germany, France, Britain,
Italy and Canada.
</TEXT>
