<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Former Owner
   Of Vernon S&amp;L
   Indicted by U.S.
   ---
   Dixon's 38 Charges Include
   Illegal Contributions
   To Political Campaigns
   ----
   By Christi Harlan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Former Texas thrift owner Don R. Dixon, a key
figure in the influence-peddling scandal that helped topple
House Speaker Jim Wright, was indicted on charges that
include illegal political contributions.
   Mr. Dixon, who owned the now-defunct Vernon Savings &amp; Loan
Association, is also charged with directing the use of Vernon
funds to pay for junkets, including "female companionship,"
for thrift executives and the then-commissioner of the Texas
Savings and Loan Department.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Dixon acquired Vernon in July 1982 and just two years
later was wrangling with federal thrift regulators who wanted
to limit the thrift's real-estate lending and explosive
growth. Mr. Dixon was among the Texas thrift operators who
sought the help of Mr. Wright and other congressmen, asking
them to intervene with the regulators.
   Ten of the 38 counts in the indictment, which was handed
up by a federal grand jury in Dallas, charge Mr. Dixon with
making false entries in Vernon's books to cover up
reimbursements to employees for their political
contributions.
   Among the politicians who received contributions from
Vernon employees, according to the indictment, were former
House Majority Whip Tony Coelho of California; former U.S.
Rep. Jack Kemp, now secretary of the U.S. Department of
Housing and Urban Development; and current U.S. Rep. Martin
Frost of Texas.
   Also receiving contributions from Vernon employees was Mr.
Wright, who resigned his congressional seat just over a year
ago after a lengthy inquiry into his personal and campaign
finances.
   The U.S. Justice Department said in a statement that the
politicians weren't aware of the improper campaign
contributions, and "there is no evidence that illegal or
improper activity was engaged in by the receiving individuals
or campaigns."
   The former Texas Savings and Loan Commissioner, L. Linton
Bowman III, who isn't accused of wrongdoing, declined to
comment on the charges that Mr. Dixon used thrift funds to
pay the commissioner's way on trips to San Diego, San
Francisco and Kansas.
   The indictment caps a 3 1/2-year investigation by the
Justice Department, which has been criticized in Congress for
its slowness in bringing criminal charges against the people
believed most responsible for the multibillion-dollar losses
in Texas thrifts.
   In apparent response to that criticism, U.S. Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh released a statement with Mr. Dixon's
indictment lauding "the hard work of our tough, persistent
investigators and prosecutors."
   "These complicated, white-collar crime cases take time to
develop, but the Justice Department is committed to the
investigation, prosecution and incarceration of those who
ripped off our financial institutions and have left the
taxpayers of the United States holding the bag," Mr.
Thornburgh said in the statement.
   When Vernon was taken over by federal thrift regulators in
1987, as much as 96% of its $1.2 billion-plus loan portfolio
was in default. The institution had wracked up millions of
dollars in losses through loans for speculative real estate
developments, many of them to friends of Mr. Dixon and other
Texas thrift owners.
   But the indictment against Mr. Dixon is only tangentially
related to the massive, fraudulent loans that helped bring
about Vernon's demise. Instead, prosecutors focused on the
sorts of charges that are comparatively easy for juries to
understand: illegal reimbursements for campaign contributions
and junkets and the diversion of loan proceeds to pay for Mr.
Dixon's California beach home.
   Prosecutors have used similar charges to win convictions
against some of Vernon's former top officers, including the
thrift's ex-president, Pat G. King.
   Because juries have shown a willingness to convict on such
charges in the past, Mr. Dixon's attorney, William M.
Ravkind, said the charges against his client will be
difficult to defend against. "I don't know how we're going to
win this one," Mr. Ravkind said.
   Mr. Dixon, if convicted of all the charges, would face a
maximum sentence of 190 years in federal prison and a fine of
as much as $9.5 million. Mr. Dixon is scheduled to surrender
to the Federal Bureau of Investigation today, and a date for
his first court appearance will be set at that time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900614-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900614-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   World Markets:
   Frankfurt Stock Prices Decline to a 1990 Low,
   As Shares Drop for the Sixth Consecutive Day
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
06/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Share prices on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange fell for the
sixth consecutive day, hitting a 1990 low.
   The German Stock Index declined 12.97 points to 1787.39,
its lowest close since Dec. 27, 1989, when the index hit
1771.44.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   London shares, meanwhile, closed just off intraday highs,
supported by sterling's strength, Wall Street's firming and
relatively hefty buying of quality stocks by institutional
investors. And Tokyo stocks bounced up from midday lows, with
the Nikkei Index finishing with modest gains after three
consecutive daily losses.
   Frankfurt's DAX Index lost more than 20 points in the
first hour of trading amid a wave of sell orders from foreign
institutional investors, breaking through what many experts
regarded as a psychological support at 1800.
   But the market quickly bounced back from its low of
1777.66 on position-squaring, and dealers said there was
little activity for the rest of the session.
   Traders said that most large institutional operators are
hesitant to invest in the Frankfurt market because the
consequences of German monetary union, set to start July 1,
aren't yet clear. In the absence of major buy orders, even
small-scale sales suffice to push the market gradually lower,
traders said.
   "There is no new money coming in," said a trader at a
Frankfurt bank. "The foreigners, who usually drive the
market, already have large German holdings and are now
waiting to see what will happen after July 1."
   If the worst fears of inflation in West Germany and
economic chaos in East Germany aren't realized, the market
has a good chance of bouncing back later this summer, he
added.
   The Frankfurt market is also suffering from the growing
attractiveness of other European markets, especially London,
which is rallying on hopes of the pound's full entry into the
European Monetary system, traders said.
   Chemical stocks were again the main losers in Frankfurt,
hurt by Hoechst's day-earlier prediction of a 10% profit
decline this year. Hoechst dropped 21.20 marks to 264.80
marks ($12.50 to $156.13), reflecting partly the payout of a
13.00-mark dividend for 1989, and other blue-chip chemicals
followed suit. Bayer dropped 7.50 marks to 294 marks, and
BASF fell 4 marks to 290.50 marks.
   Schering, a chemical and pharmaceutical issue, tumbled
12.50 marks to 787 marks after predicting flat earnings for
the year.
   Electronics stock Siemens also fell, dropping 6.40 marks
to 705.60 marks because of the scaling-down of profit
forecasts by some analysts.
   But most other blue-chip shares declined less than 5
marks. In the auto sector, Bayerische Motoren Werke declined
4 marks to 566 marks, Volkswagen eased 1.10 marks to 594
marks, and Daimler-Benz edged down 1 mark to 798 marks.
   Among banking stocks, Deutsche Bank and Commerzbank shed 2
marks each to 754 marks and 269.50 marks, respectively, while
Dresdner Bank slid 1 mark to 407 marks.
   Among the few gainers was retailing stock Karstadt, which
jumped 10 marks to 655 marks.
   Tire maker Continental rose 3.80 marks to 312.80 marks on
speculation that the annual shareholder meeting at the end of
June will vote to eliminate the company's 5% voting right
restriction. That could pave the way for an eventual takeover
by another tire group.
   In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 Share
Index gained 34.7 points to 2405.4, after being up as many as
39.6 points.
   Dealers said that market's fortunes are tied to Wall
Street. Although some expect London to continue steady, there
is considerable uncertainty and wariness about its underlying
strength.
   However, London is also currently heavily influenced by
futures, which are still trading at a healthy premium to
cash. The June FT-SE 100 index contract ended trading
yesterday at 2431.5, up from Tuesday's close of 2398.
   The Financial Times 30 Share Index gained 32.2 points to
1933.2. Volume was 611.2 million shares, up from 433.7
million issues Tuesday.
   Gains were broad-based, without any one sector benefiting
the most. British Aerospace gained 27 pence to 571 pence (46
cents to $9.73), while BOC rose 18.5 pence to 590 pence.
   ICI gained 16 pence to #12.51, as the market discounted
media reports about regulatory concerns over its heart drug,
Corwin. In addition, ICI is expected to benefit from
sterling's entry into the European Monetary System, dealers
said.
   Tokyo's Nikkei index of 225 issues advanced 49.46 points
to 32371.77 on Wednesday. Volume on the first section was
estimated at 450 million shares, in line with 478.6 million
shares Tuesday. Decliners outnumbered gainers 522 to 402,
while 202 issues were unchanged.
   In early trading in Tokyo Thursday, the Nikkei index rose
191.80 points to 32563.57.
   On Wednesday, the Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues
listed in the first section edged down, however, slipping
2.15 points, or 0.09%, to 2378.41.
   The second section index rose 21.32 points, or 0.52%, to
4086.12. Volume in the section was estimated at 30 million
shares, up from 18.1 million shares Tuesday.
   Because of the continuing weakness of the yen and bond
prices, most investors remained on the sidelines, traders
said.
   Investors bought stocks with high export ratios, as those
issues benefit from the weaker yen, traders said. But as many
of these shares declined from early highs on profit-taking,
the Nikkei Index gradually extended losses during the
afternoon.
   Shipbuilding and other shares that had advanced strongly
earlier this month and then turned downward in the past few
days remained at lower levels most of the day.
   Elsewhere, prices closed higher in Amsterdam, Paris and
Zurich, lower in Milan, Madrid, Frankfurt and Brussels and
mixed in Stockholm. South African gold stocks closed sharply
lower.
   Prices also ended higher in Sydney, Taipei, and Manila,
and lower in Hong Kong, Singapore, Seoul and Wellington.
                                                                                                       

   Here are price trends on the world's major stock markets,
as calculated by Morgan Stanley Capital International
Perspective, Geneva. To make them directly comparable, each
index is based on the close of 1969 equaling 100. The
percentage change is since year-end.
                                                                                                       

                                                                                                       

